      {
        "feedback": "Correct! The end of the verb (-o, -as, -a, -amos) changes depending on who represents the subject (Yo, Tú, Ella, Nosotros).",
        "isCorrect": true,
        "text": "The verb ending changes to match the subject (person)"
      },
      {
        "feedback": "Look closer at the endings. While they share the root 'habl-', the endings (-o, -as, -a, -amos) are all different.",
        "isCorrect": false,
        "text": "The verbs stay exactly the same for every person"
      },
      {
        "feedback": "Not quite. Only the 'Yo' form ends in -o. The other subjects use different endings like -as and -a.",
        "isCorrect": false,
        "text": "Spanish verbs always end in -o"
      },
      {
        "feedback": "The verb usually comes after the subject in these examples, but the key pattern is the changing ending, not the position.",
        "isCorrect": false,
        "text": "The verb always comes at the end of the sentence"
      }
    ],
    "question": "Look at the highlighted words. What pattern do you notice?"
  },
  "examples": [
    {
      "highlight": "hablo",
      "romanization": "",
      "sentence": "Yo hablo español.",
      "translation": "I speak Spanish."
    },
    {
      "highlight": "hablas",
      "romanization": "",
      "sentence": "Tú hablas inglés.",
      "translation": "You speak English."
    },
    {
      "highlight": "habla",
      "romanization": "",
      "sentence": "Ella habla francés.",
      "translation": "She speaks French."
    },
    {
      "highlight": "hablamos",
      "romanization": "",
      "sentence": "Nosotros hablamos mucho.",
      "translation": "We speak a lot."
    }
  ],
